Partisan Vision? Impact of Partisanship on Visual Evaluative Tasks

Do partisans see things differently? We test the hypothesis with two different experiments and a survey. In the experiments, we manipulate who has written a piece of text, or parked the cars and ask respondents to estimate the number of errors. And on the survey question, we ask respondents to count how many people are wearing a mask at a Trump rally. We find that the differences are consistently small.

Results

Authors

Gaurav Sood and Alex Theodoridis
